  url = {http://www.atrf.info/papers/2012/index.aspxhttps://trid.trb.org/view/1224107},
  abstract = {To assess the travel choices and current level of transport accessibility for people with disability in Western Australia, the Department of Transport conducted a survey in 2012 amongst people with a range of disability and their carers.  A total of 608 people completed the survey, 37 per cent male and 63 per cent female. The average age category was 45 \&ndash; 54 years old with a majority of people from the Multiple Sclerosis Society (37 per cent) and the Association for the Blind (25 per cent). Almost all of the respondents (96 per cent) had public transport in their local area and 68 per cent used it at least once per month. In contrast, 92 per cent of respondents were either a passenger or driver of a private vehicle at least once per month. With respect to weekly transport choices, the most common mode of accessing work, recreation, shopping, education and medical appointments was the private vehicle (63 per cent followed by walking (17 per cent). Public transport accounted for 5 \&ndash; 20 per cent of transport depending on the purpose of the destinations.  The results suggest that it is vitally important to continue implementing the Disability Standards for Accessible Public Transport Standards (2002) and improve access for people with disability to public transport, including taxis. Transport policy, however, should also consider further measures that maintain or improve access to a private vehicle for people with disability who need to use this mode of transport in order to avoid transport disadvantage. In addition, continued improvements in the local built environment (e.g. footpaths and connectivity) which facilitate walking for people with disability, especially to access local facilities and public transport, are also necessary to reduce transport disadvantage.}
