  publisher = {{Elsevier}},
  url = {https://trid.trb.org/view/728163},
  abstract = {Many proponents of congestion pricing policies base their support on its demonstrated economic efficiency, with congestion pricing being viewed as a desirable policy within a standard welfare economic framework.  In contrast, this paper argues that as the goal of transportation policy shifts from promotion of mobility to improvement of accessibility, the desirability of congestion pricing policies becomes conditional upon specific elements of their design.  This mobility-accessibility distinction is used to distinguish different implementations of congestion pricing.  A mobility-based congestion pricing promises to alleviate congestion but threatens to deteriorate from overall regional accessibility as it accelerates metropolitan deconcentration. Accessibility-based congestion pricing avoids acceleration of sprawl by incorporating policies to ensure that drivers who are priced off roads are replaced with residents and travelers arriving at previously congested areas by other means. Without such policies, the economic vitality of congested areas would be threatened by the restriction of customer and employee flows.  It also is argued that a mobility-based policy will tend to concentrate benefits at the high end of the income spectrum, while an accessibility-based policy will spread benefits more equitably.}
}

