  url = {https://trid.trb.org/view/803416},
  abstract = {At present, only 3.2\% of children in the United States ride their bikes to school daily, completing 40\% fewer trips compared with a generation ago.  This article reports on a study undertaken to examine biking suitability (bikeability) and prevalence of biking in 14 elementary schools in Mesa, Arizona.  Children in these schools were bused to school in ranges from 2.4\% to 53.6\% of the student population.  Street segments (within 0.25-mile radius of school) were scored for bikeability and bikes in racks per school student population established biking prevalence.  Thirteen schools scored very good and one scored fair for biking suitability.  Median biking prevalence was 3.1\% in the low-busing schools and 1.3\% in the high-busing schools, considered relatively low in both low- and high-busing schools. The authors conclude with a discussion of the other issues that are likely to contribute to commuting mode, including individual, social patterns, safety, convenience, school, and community factors.}
